    "contentHtml": "<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Have you ever noticed that the same watch face can look a bit different on different Garmin watches?</p><p style=\"text-align: left;\">For example, on a watch with an <strong>AMOLED display</strong>, the colors appear bright and vivid, while on a <strong>MIP display</strong>, they tend to look softer and more subdued.</p><p style=\"text-align: left;\">This isn’t your imagination — it’s because each watch model has a different <strong>Color Depth</strong>, which determines how many colors the screen can display.</p><p style=\"text-align: left;\"><br></p><hr/><p>🎨 <strong>What Is Color Depth?</strong><br><strong>Color Depth</strong> refers to the number of colors a screen can display.</p><p>You can think of it as <em>“how many different paints you have on your palette.”</em><br><br>The more colors your screen supports, the richer and smoother the transitions between shades will look.</p><hr/><p><br></p><p>🎨 <strong>What Is Color Depth?</strong><br><strong>Color Depth</strong> refers to how many colors a screen can display — imagine it as <em>how many paints your palette can hold.</em></p><p><br></p><table style=\"width: auto;\"><tbody><tr><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Bit Depth</th><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Number of Colors</th><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Typical Example</th></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\"><strong>4-bit</strong></td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">16 colors</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Early e-ink or monochrome displays</td></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\"><strong>8-bit</strong></td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">256 colors</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Standard MIP screens</td></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\"><strong>16-bit</strong></td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">65,536 colors</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Most AMOLED screens</td></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\"><strong>24-bit</strong></td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">16,777,216 colors</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">True full-color high-definition displays</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The higher the color depth, the smoother the gradients and the richer the visual details.</p><hr/><p><br></p><p>🎨 <strong>Color Palette Examples</strong></p><ul><li>16-color palette</li></ul><p><img src=\"https://cdn.wristo.io/product/5168578d1b7a4c73b08ffa25d3191a72/original.png\" alt=\"image.png\" data-href=\"https://cdn.wristo.io/product/5168578d1b7a4c73b08ffa25d3191a72/original.png\" style=\"width: 50%;\"/></p><ul><li>RGB222: 64-color palette</li></ul><p><img src=\"https://cdn.wristo.io/product/2f5abf2232d3472d910cf55001d92a1f/original.png\" alt=\"image.png\" data-href=\"https://cdn.wristo.io/product/2f5abf2232d3472d910cf55001d92a1f/original.png\" style=\"width: 100%;\"/></p><hr/><p><br></p><p>🖥️ <strong>Garmin Display Types</strong><br><br>Garmin watches mainly use two types of displays:</p><ol><li>MIP (Memory In Pixel) Pros: Extremely power-efficient, readable in sunlight. Traits: Limited colors (typically 8–64), soft visual style. Used in: Fēnix, Instinct, Forerunner series.</li><li>AMOLED Pros: Vivid colors, high contrast, pure blacks. Traits: Supports tens of thousands of colors but consumes more power. Used in: Venu, Epix, MARQ, Forerunner (high-end models).</li></ol><p>That’s why the same watch face may appear as <strong>bright blue and deep black</strong> on an AMOLED screen but <strong>soft sky blue and grayish black</strong> on a MIP display.</p><hr/><p><br></p><p>💡 <strong>How Wristo Adapts to Different Devices</strong><br><br>To ensure the best viewing experience on every watch, <strong>Wristo</strong> automatically adjusts its color palette based on your device’s display type and color depth.</p><p><br></p><table style=\"width: auto;\"><tbody><tr><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Device Type</th><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Optimization Strategy</th></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">🟢 Low-color-depth devices</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Simplified colors for crisp contrast</td></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">🔵 High-color-depth devices</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Enhanced gradients and lighting effects</td></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">⚫ AOD (Always-On Display) mode</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Darker tones to extend battery life</td></tr></tbody></table><p>So what you see on Wristo isn’t just <em>beautiful</em> — it’s <em>custom-tuned beauty</em> for your specific watch.</p><hr/><p><br></p><p>📊 <strong>What Does This Mean for You?</strong></p><ul><li>Different colors ≠ watch face error — it’s optimized for your device.</li><li>Fewer colors in power-saving mode — to extend battery life.</li><li>Newer devices — richer colors, higher brightness, smoother animations.</li></ul><hr/><p><br></p><p>🔬 <strong>Pro Tip: Bitmap Optimization & Power Efficiency</strong><br><br>Garmin officially recommends using <strong>lower color depths and limited palettes</strong> when designing watch faces.<br><br>This not only reduces package size but also makes watch faces run more smoothly.</p><p>👉 Learn more: <em>How to Optimize Garmin Bitmaps (Official Guide)</em></p><hr/><p><br></p><p>🪶 <strong>Summary</strong></p><p><br></p><table style=\"width: auto;\"><tbody><tr><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Display Type</th><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Characteristics</th><th colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Wristo Optimization</th></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\"><strong>MIP</strong></td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Limited colors, long battery life</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">High-contrast colors emphasizing key data</td></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\"><strong>AMOLED</strong></td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Rich, high-contrast colors</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Gradients and soft lighting for aesthetics</td></tr><tr><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\"><strong>Always-On</strong></td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Power-saving display</td><td colSpan=\"1\" rowSpan=\"1\" width=\"auto\">Reduced brightness and highlights</td></tr></tbody></table><hr/><p><br></p><p>💬 <strong>In One Sentence</strong><br><em>What you see isn’t just color — it’s Wristo’s finely tuned visual language, crafted for your watch.</em></p><p><br></p><p><br></p>",
